        <h3><a href="/">Submission Guidelines</a></h3>

        <small>(These guidelines have been adopted from the well written Hacker News guidelines)</small>
        <h3>What to Submit</h3>

        <p>On-Topic: Anything that Swift developers would find interesting. That includes more than tutorials and GitHub projects. It could also included interesting iOS API news, related open source Swift developments, Swift Linux news or even tangential related Apple news (i.e. WWDC announcement). </p>

        <p>Off-Topic: Everything else, particularly plain Apple news or other programming languages' content.
        </p>

        <h3>In Submissions</h3>

        <p>Please don't do things to make titles stand out, like using uppercase or exclamation points, or adding a parenthetical remark saying how great an article is. It's implicit in submitting something that you think it's important.
        </p>
        <p>If you submit a link to a video or pdf, please warn us by appending [video] or [pdf] to the title.
        </p>
        <p>Please submit the original source. If a post reports on something found on another site, submit the latter.
        </p>
        <p>If the original title includes the name of the site, please take it out, because the site name will be displayed after the link.
        </p>
        <p>Use the original title, unless it is misleading or linkbait.
        </p>
        <p>Please don't submit so many links at once that the new page is dominated by your submissions.
        </p>

        <h3>In Comments</h3>

        <p>Be civil. Don't say things you wouldn't say in a face-to-face conversation. Avoid gratuitous negativity.
        </p>
        <p>When disagreeing, please reply to the argument instead of calling names. E.g. "That is idiotic; 1 + 1 is 2, not 3" can be shortened to "1 + 1 is 2, not 3."
        </p>
        <p>Please don't insinuate that someone hasn't read an article. "Did you even read the article? It mentions that" can be shortened to "The article mentions that."
        </p>
